{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517543"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.33,0.05,0.5,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107596"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5253"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90045"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42815"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107596"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with palpitations occurring intermittently over the past few months. He reports no associated shortness of breath or collapses. His medical history includes hypertension, rheumatic fever and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His regular medications include ramipril, metformin and empagliflozin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 88/min (irregular), blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has an irregularly irregular heart rhythm. His heart sounds are dual with a mid diastolic murmur in the left axilla. His chest is clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis ECG demonstrates atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Dabigatran","Clopidogrel","Warfarin","Fondaparinux"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is a 78-year-old man with a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus who is found to have atrial fibrillation (AF). His mid diastolic murmur in the left axilla indicates the presence of mitral stenosis, and given his history of rheumatic fever this patient is likely to have rheumatic mitral stenosis. This has been termed \u0027valvular AF\u0027, although this terminology is no longer recommended. For patients with rheumatic mitral stenosis, anticoagulation therapy is particularly important due to the increased risk of thrombus formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated and the most appropriate choice. Warfarin works by inhibiting the production of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors, and its efficacy is measured by the international normalised ratio (INR). The target INR for patients with mitral stenosis and atrial fibrillation is 2-3. A higher target of 2.5-3.5 is only used if there is also a mechanical heart valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E is direct oral anticoagulants (DOAC) that could be considered as an alternative to warfarin, but it is only used in the setting of atrial fibrillation that is not associated with rheumatic mitral stenosis (or a mechanical heart valve).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFondaparinux\u003C/strong\u003E is a newer injectable anticoagulant that inhibits factor Xa, a clotting factor. It has been shown to be non-inferior to enoxaparin (a low molecular weight heparin) in preventing venous thromboembolism. It is used in treatment and prophylaxis for venous thromboembolism, not for atrial fibrillation and stroke prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiplatelet medication, not an anticoagulant. Patients with atrial fibrillation require anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiplatelet medication, not an anticoagulant. Patients with atrial fibrillation require anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Warfarin is the recommended anticoagulant for patients with rheumatic mitral stenosis and atrial fibrillation (valvular AF)","Direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are contraindicated in patients with moderate to severe rheumatic mitral stenosis","The target INR for patients with mitral stenosis and atrial fibrillation is 2-3"],"references":["Hess PL, Gosch KL, Jani SM, Varosy PD, Bradley SM, Maddox TM, Michael Ho P, Virani SS. Use of oral anticoagulants in patients with valvular atrial fibrillation: findings from the NCDR PINNACLE Registry. Am Heart J. 2021 Oct;240:58-62. doi: 10.1016/j.ahj.2021.04.017. Epub 2021 May 24. PMID: 34033802."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90045"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T10:28:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T10:29:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107596"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/98"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hy